<br>
Each ton of hydrogen produced will require (Correct me if I am wrong) the manufacture of around 50 tons of sulphuric acid. Also, how “Fast” is the reaction? (IE to produce 1 ton H2/day, how many tons of H2SO4 do you need in the “loop” at any one time IYSWIM)<br>
<br>
ISTM that to use this process to provide for a hydrogen economy would involve the manufacture of hundreds of millions of tons of acid pa (increasing to billions)<br>
<br>
Even as a closed loop system with full recycling of the SO2. 100% recycling is unlikely to be achieved and some releases are going to take place either as a routine or as a result of accidents. <br>
<br>
Given the large amount of chemicals involved, even a tiny escape (%age wise) can add up to large amounts of materials which, as well as being nasty in their own right, will also have to be replaced using mined sulphur.<br>
<br>
Don’t get me wrong; I’m not trying to knock the idea. Being able to utilise nuclear heat (or any other high temperature heat source for that matter) directly in this way provides for intriguing possibilities.<br>
<br>
I’m just wondering what thought has been put into the problems of scaling this up from the lab to full industrial scale production, And how those problems may be addressed?<br>
<br>
